ce:section.ce:para:
As the nitrogen-doped carbon dots derived from Morinda coreia fruits have good photophysical properties, preliminary screening of their fluorescence behaviour is done on MCCDs with selected metal cations of 250 μM concentrations (Fig. 5
                        a). It is seen that many of the chosen metal cations do reduce the PL intensity of MCCDs slightly but Fe3+ ions are unique as more than 50 % of PL intensity of them are reduced with 250 μM Fe3+ (Fig. S3). Photographic images showing the quenching of fluorescence of MCCDs by Fe3+ and other metal ions is were taken in a UV chamber and are given in Fig. S4. It is very clear from Fig. S4 (a) that though the fluorescent intensities are quenched, they are not very clearly seen in the long UV wavelengths because of the additional yellow-based colour interferences caused by ferric solution. But when the images were recorded in the short wavelength irradiation in the UV chamber, fluorescent quenching of MCCDs is very clearly seen in Fig. S4 (b). In order to confirm the selectivity of Fe3+ ions in the fluorescence quenching of MCCDs, ferric ions are added to (MCCDs + other metal ion) mixtures and the results as images are provided in Fig. S5. The images clearly show that unlike the situation in Fig S4, where fluorescence is almost eliminated only in presence of Fe3+, all solutions are found with significantly reduced PL intensities as all of them are added with Fe3+ ions. Concentration dependency of Fe3+ ions alone is, therefore, tested with MCCDs and the PL spectra recorded with varying iron concentrations as given in Fig. 5b. The fluorescence response of MCCDs towards ferric ions of different concentrations are given in Fig. S6 and it is found that there is a linear relationship up to a concentration of 25 μM and (inset in Fig. S6). The linear equation was found to be y = 0.3678x with high correlation (R2 = 0.9898). Limit of detection (LOD) is found from the 3σ/S formula, where S represents the slope of the above linear fit and σ represents the standard deviation in PL intensity of 11 blank determinations [46]. The value of LOD was found to be 1.32 μM which is well below the threshold value of 5.36 μM for Fe3+ in drinking water set by USEPA [47]. An attempt has been made to compare the sensing ability of MCCDs towards Fe3+ in water by various NCQDs and CQDs reported recently (Table 1
                        ). Though there are many works in which the LOD for Fe3+ is less than 1 μM, the detection limit of MCCDs is comparable with many of them. Further, the carbon dots reported in this work are prepared from Morinda coreia fruits which have no commercial value and no chemicals are used during the preparation.
